All students grades Pre-K through 12 must return their registration packets to their teacher or the office.
Please provide valid information so we can contact you in regards to your child and send messages related to attendance, emergencies, or inclement weather. There are also forms on our open campus policy for lunch as well as allergy/medical alerts and more.
In this packet is also our Release of Student Work and Image form. This allows us to brag on your students here on our website and school Facebook page, and send their accomplishments to our local newspaper when applicable!
Please fill out the forms and return your packet as soon as possible!

post_text: Yearbook Update: All yearbooks should finish printing and ship out in the next six weeks!
shared_text:
Greyhound Yearbook Class
August 10 at 2:00 PM ·

We KNOW you are feeling ANTSY. We've seen you checking our page for updates, and we sincerely apologize for the radio silence! The truth is, there has not been anything we could tell you - UNTIL TODAY, that is!
Today our Lifetouch rep called and gave us the best ETA she possibly could. All yearbooks should finish printing and ship out in the next six weeks! We do not have an exact date or tracking information yet, but it is refreshing to know that within the next six weeks, we will have our gorgeous yearbook in our hands!
Keep checking back on our page for updates and for sneak peeks at our 2020 Greyhound Yearbook! This Friday, August 14th, we will share our dedication page here, and we know you're going to love it.

Reminder: Here are our Strawn Elementary school supply lists. At this moment, we are not posting lists for Junior High or High School. If you have a student in grades 6 through 12, we are only asking for pens, pencils, and notebook paper at this time.
Tax Free Weekend begins this Friday, August 7th. If you choose to participate in this in-person, please stay safe and wear a mask! We are all very excited for our 2020 Graduates tonight. Their health and safety is our top priority, so please follow our protocols and do not attend if you have had contact with someone with or are experiencing any of the listed symptoms. As a reminder, here are the precautions for tonight's graduation ceremony. Please remember to submit your screening form via e-mail or bring it with you tonight.
If you are unable to attend, the ceremony will be live streamed at 7:00 PM on the Strawn Greyhound Football page, which you can find here: https://www.facebook.com/Strawn-Greyhound-Football-721784208168816/

post_text:
At tonight's School Board meeting, Mindy Hodgkins (President) and Jim Pollock (Vice President) retired from many years on the school board. The two received plaques to thank them for their time serving the District on the Board of Trustees. Brad Couger and Chris Nuñez were sworn in tonight as well. Our 2020-2021 School Board of Trustees consists of Tina Spakes (President), Craig Abbott (Vice President), Jessica Lopez Mallory (Secretary), Brandi Sizemore, Brad Couger, and Chris Nuñez.
Thank you for your service and dedication to Strawn ISD and our community!

Tomorrow is our last Packet Return Day! Please make sure all online assignments are completed. Bring your paper assignments, textbooks, Chromebook with case & charger, any school issued calculators, and library books to the new gym parking lot. Remain in your vehicle and our staff will come out to assist you! Please attempt to be at the drop off point at your designated time slot to avoid overcrowding. The designated family time slots are arranged by Oldest Sibling's Last Name:
A-H 8:00-9:00 AM
L-R 9:00-10:00 AM
S-Z 10:00-11:00 AM
It's been an odd but great year with our Greyhounds, and we hope you all have a safe, fun summer!

Tomorrow is Packet Pick Up & Return Day!
We only have a few weeks left in the school year. Please make sure you have all your online assignments turned in, and bring back your completed work & any library books you may still have. Come to the parking lot in front of the New Gym. Remain in your vehicle and the SISD staff will have your materials ready to deliver. Your students do not need to attend. Please attempt to be at the pick up point at your designated time slot to avoid overcrowding. The designated family time slots are arranged by Oldest Sibling's Last Name:
A-H 8:00-9:00 AM
L-R 9:00-10:00 AM
S-Z 10:00-11:00 AM
Please contact the school if we can assist your family in any way!

Please contact us so we can honor your Senior in the 2019-2020 Greyhound Yearbook.
We can work with you on payment, but we MUST have your photos and message to create your senior page. Please contact Mrs. Ellis to make arrangements.
shared_text:
Greyhound Yearbook Class
April 29 at 9:02 AM ·

The deadline is here and we have not heard from many senior parents. So far, only 3 out of 17 have sent payment or photos. We are willing to work with you on payment, but we MUST have your photos and message in order to create your senior page.
Please contact Mrs. Ellis as soon as possible to make arrangements. You may message us here via Facebook Messenger, e-mail cassie.ellis@strawnschool.net, call the office Thursday morning (254) 672-5776, or call her cell. That number is printed on the letters that were mailed home to senior parents last week.
Please contact us so we can honor your senior in the 2019-2020 Greyhound Yearbook.

Ms. Harris's 3rd Grade Class and Mrs. Milner's Kindergarten Class were assigned peeps to take care of for a week! They named them, and designed a bed and blanket for them. Third Grade did writing and grammar with theirs as well! Kindergarten built a house for their peeps, and drew and labeled the peeps' bedroom. Some even had twins!

Visit the National Autism Association website for resources, guides, and tips for families and schools.
"Different and beautiful.
Different and amazing.
Different and equal.
Different, not less."

post_text:
4th and 5th Grade will be doing a service project for each month of the remaining school year. This month they have chosen to collect items to put in care packages for the homeless. Amy May, who hands out these care packages with her daughter, Emma, came today to speak with grades Pre-K through 12 about items that would be appreciated. She also shared some very touching experiences, like how something as simple as a nail file or a fork can make someone feel human again. Thank you for coming to visit with us!
We will be collecting items for these packages throughout the month of March. Some ideas are non-perishable food items (Make sure cans have a pull tab!), toiletries like soap or wet wipes (Grab those freebies at hotels!), new socks, bottled water, and even the bags themselves. Let's take the opportunity to give back and make a difference in someone's life!

post_text:
Each year, IXL recognizes the top teachers in the world. These educators were selected as top teachers based on their students' time spent on IXL. With more than 400,000 teachers using IXL worldwide, the Elite 100 truly stand out for their innovation, creativity, and passion in motivating their students to succeed.
For the 2018-2019 school year, three of the Elite 100 are from Texas, and one of those is Strawn ISD's Kindergarten teacher, Mrs. Paula Milner! Congratulations, and thank you for educating and encouraging our young minds! She says, "We set goals and when we reach our goals students are rewarded with different prizes such as lunch in the classroom, slipper day or getting to sit anywhere in the class. We also use a sticker chart to hold ourselves accountable. We are good at encouraging each other. My favorite thing they say to each other is 'You got this!'"
To read her full statement, visit https://www.ixl.com/resources/elite-100

post_text:
Mrs. Shugart's Seventh Grade Science students are currently working on a unit covering Reproduction and Heredity. At the end of January, they were to create a project that represented the cell cycle with the main focus being on Mitosis - the forming of two nuclei, each with a complete copy of DNA. The 7th graders learned that this is the process that allows their bodies to grow and repair, and it ties in with reproduction. Their models had to represent the phases that cells progress through in order for this to occur.
Now, they are currently working on heredity. With this project, the students were given information concerning the genetic makeup of two parent plants. With this information and content learned in class, students predicted the outcome of their flowers. The project for this assignment consisted of a drawing of their flower.
Well, done Seventh Grade Science!

post_text: Strawn ISD applied for the 2019-2021 School Safety Security Grant that was included in Senate Bill 500 from the 86th Texas Legislature. All funds available are to be utilized for school safety and security. After completing a safety assessment of Strawn ISD, we determined that updated perimeter security fencing was the best choice. We have been working with BUZZ Custom Fence with development, proposals, and installation. Additional security fencing around Strawn School campus will continue and be completed by the end of the 2019-2020 academic school year.
text: Strawn ISD applied for the 2019-2021 School Safety Security Grant that was included in Senate Bill 500 from the 86th Texas Legislature. All funds available are to be utilized for school safety and security. After completing a safety assessment of Strawn ISD, we determined that updated perimeter security fencing was the best choice. We have been working with BUZZ Custom Fence with development, proposals, and installation. Additional security fencing around Strawn School campus will continue and be completed by the end of the 2019-2020 academic school year.
